{"type": "user", "message": {"role": "user", "content": [{"tool_use_id": "chatcmpl-tool-94205966c88685d0", "type": "tool_result", "content": "1\t=== PAGE 1 ===\n2\t Cross Domain Few-Shot Class-Incremental Audio Classification Via \n3\tAdversarial Contrastive Learning  \n4\tYongjie Si, Yanxiong Li*, Sen Huang, Beibei Liu  \n5\tSchool of Electronic and Information Engineering, South China University of Technology, Guangzhou, China  \n6\teeyongjiesi@mail.scut.edu.cn, eeyxli@scut.edu.cn, huangsen@scut.edu.cn, eebbliu@scut.edu.cn \n7\t \n8\tAbstract \n9\tCurrent Few-shot Class-incremental Audio Classification \n10\t(FCAC) methods assume that samples of base and incremental \n11\tclasses are in the same domain (following the same distribution). \n12\tHowever, there is generally a domain shift between the above \n13\ttwo types of samples. In this paper, we explore the problem of \n14\tCross Domain FCAC where samples of base and incremental \n15\tclasses have domain shift. We propose a strategy of adversarial \n16\tcontrastive training which enables the model to effectively \n17\tclassify samples of different classes from unseen domains. The \n18\tmodel consists of an encoder and a classifier. The encoder is \n19\ttrained in base session but frozen in incremental sessions, \n20\twhereas the classifier is trained in all sessions. Experiments are \n21\tdone on six pairs of cross-domain datasets. Results show that \n22\tour method exceeds state-of-the-art methods in average \n23\taccuracy. The code is at https://github.com/YongjieSi/ACL. \n24\tIndex Terms: Few-shot class-incremental learning, audio \n25\tclassification, cross domain, adversarial contrastive learning \n26\t1. Introduction \n27\tAudio classification (AC) is a task to identify different audio \n28\tclasses. It has widespread applications, such as wildlife \n29\tprotection [1], road surveillance [2], classification of acoustic \n30\tscene [3], video analysis [4] and speaker analysis [5]. Many AC \n31\tmethods [6]-[9] require abundant samples of predefined classes \n32\tfor model training. The trained model generally lacks the ability \n33\tto recognize new classes. In real applications, the number of \n34\tclasses is not fixed but dynamically changes and the number of \n35\ttraining samples per class is generally limited. To address \n36\tchallenges such as the variable number of classes and scarcity \n37\tof training samples per class, Few-shot Class-incremental \n38\tAudio Classification (FCAC) methods are proposed [10]-[16]. \n39\tThey can continually identify new classes using a few training \n40\tsamples per class and meanwhile memorize old ones. A \n41\tcommon practice in the FCAC methods is to decompose the \n42\tmodel into an encoder and a classifier. Existing FCAC methods \n43\thave different technical characteristics, such as Dynamic Few-\n44\tShot Learning (DFSL) [10], prototype-based classifier [11]-\n45\t[13], stochastic classifier [14], linear classifier [15], [16], and \n46\tridge regression classifier [17].  \n47\tThe above efforts have contributed to the development of \n48\tAC, but they still leave something to be improved. For example, \n49\tthese methods assume that the samples of different classes in \n50\tboth base and incremental sessions are from the same domain. \n51\tHowever, there is a domain shift between the samples from base \n52\tand incremental sessions in many applications. In this paper, we \n53\ttackle a new and practical problem in which domain shift and \n54\tclass increment coexist in different session. This problem is \n55\tcalled Cross Domain FCAC (CD-FCAC). It is an extension of \n56\tthe FCAC problem which does not consider the domain shift of \n57\tsamples from different sessions. To our best knowledge, the \n58\twork in this paper is the first effort to solve the CD-FCAC \n59\tproblem. The motivation for doing this work is due to the \n60\texistence of CD-FCAC problems in many practical applications. \n61\tFor example, in smart home scenarios, the intelligent agents \n62\tneed to incrementally recognize different audio classes (such as \n63\tvoice commands, environmental sounds, and musical sounds) \n64\tfrom different domains (e.g., different datasets). \n65\tIn addition to the catastrophic forgetting of old classes in \n66\tincremental learning, there are two key challenges in the CD-\n67\tFCAC. First, there is domain shift between samples of both \n68\tbase and incremental classes. Second, there is label difference \n69\tbetween base and incremental classes. To obtain high accuracy, \n70\tthe model needs to have strong ability to overcome the impacts \n71\tof class increment and domain shift. To address the above two \n72\tchallenges, we propose a strategy of adversarial contrastive \n73\ttraining which adopts both adversarial training and contrastive \n74\tloss. To alleviate domain shift, diverse adversarial samples are \n75\tgenerated to simulate pseudo-target domains. They and the \n76\tsource-domain samples are used together to train the model for \n77\textracting domain-invariant embeddings. To enable the model \n78\tto generalize well to unseen classes, we use the loss of \n79\tsupervised contrastive learning for training the model in the \n80\tbase session. This loss aims to aggregate the embeddings of \n81\tsamples of the same class while keeping the embeddings of \n82\tsamples of different classes away from each other. Hence, the \n83\tembeddings are expected to be intra-class compact and inter-\n84\tclass separable, which allows the classifier to establish robust \n85\tdecision boundaries based on a few samples of new classes. To \n86\tprevent the model from forgetting the knowledge of old classes, \n87\tthe encoder is frozen and mean vectors of old classes’ \n88\tembeddings are saved in each incremental session, while the \n89\tclassifier is updated for learning new classes in each session. \n90\tExperiments are done on six pairs of cross-domain datasets \n91\tfrom three public datasets of the LS-100, NSynth-100, and \n92\tFSC-89 [17]. Results show that our method exceeds previous \n93\tmethods in average accuracy. The contributions of the work are \n94\tsummarized as follows. \n95\t1) We explore a new problem of CD-FCAC where the \n96\tdomain shift and class increment coexist.  \n97\t2) We propose an adversarial contrastive training strategy \n98\twhich is a fusion of adversarial training and contrastive learning.  \n99\t3) We propose a CD-FCAC method which exceeds state-\n100\tof-the-art methods in average accuracy.  \n101\t2. Method \n102\t2.1. Problem Definition \n103\tThe CD-FCAC consists of M sessions, including one base \n104\tsession (session 0) and (M-1) incremental sessions (sessions 1 \n105\tto (M-1)). we consider a user-friendly setting where the samples \n106\t \n107\t* Corresponding author: Yanxiong Li (eeyxli@scut.edu.cn).\n108\t\n109\t\n110\t=== PAGE 2 ===\n111\tin base session are from a single source domain, while the \n112\tsamples in incremental sessions are from another domain. The \n113\tbase classes (in the base session) and incremental classes (in the \n114\tincremental sessions) are called source-domain classes and \n115\ttarget-domain classes, respectively. In addition, audio classes \n116\tin the prior and current sessions are called old and new classes, \n117\trespectively. The training and testing datasets of different \n118\tsessions are {𝑫଴\n119\t௧௥, 𝑫ଵ\n120\t௧௥, ..., 𝑫௠\n121\t௧௥, ..., 𝑫ெିଵ\n122\t௧௥\n123\t} and {𝑫଴\n124\t௧௘, 𝑫ଵ\n125\t௧௘, ..., \n126\t𝑫௠\n127\t௧௘, ..., 𝑫ெିଵ\n128\t௧௘\n129\t}, respectively. 𝑫௠\n130\t௧௥ and 𝑫௠\n131\t௧௘ have the same \n132\tlabel set Lm. The datasets in various sessions don’t have the \n133\tsame classes, namely ∀m, h and m ≠ h, Lm ∩ Lh = ϕ. In the mth \n134\tsession, only 𝑫௠\n135\t௧௥ can be used to train the model, and the \n136\ttrained model is tested on the testing datasets of current and all \n137\tprevious sessions, namely 𝑫଴\n138\t௧௘∪𝑫ଵ\n139\t௧௘...∪𝑫௠\n140\t௧௘. The dataset 𝑫଴\n141\t௧௥ \n142\thas many classes and each class has sufficient training samples, \n143\twhile the dataset 𝑫௠\n144\t௧௥ (1≤m≤(M-1)) only has N classes and \n145\teach class only has K training samples.  \n146\t2.2. Method Framework \n147\tEncoder\n148\tSource domain audio \n149\tsamples   from  D0\n150\tLog Mel-spectra X \n151\tClassifier\n152\tSpectral disruptor\n153\tℓmax\n154\t: Frozen\n155\t: Active\n156\tMLP\n157\ttr\n158\tℓce\n159\tℓscl\n160\t: Forward\n161\tGenerating adversarial samples\n162\t(Maximizing training step)\n163\tℓmin\n164\tEncoder\n165\tAdversarial samples  X \n166\tClassifier\n167\tC\n168\tα\n169\tβ\n170\t Training the model\n171\t(Minimizing training step)\n172\t: Backward\n173\tBase training（m=0）\n174\tLog Mel-\n175\tspectra X \n176\tAudio \n177\tsamples Dm\n178\tClassifier\n179\tEncoder\n180\t λ\n181\tℓinc\n182\tℓce\n183\tℓce\n184\tnew\n185\told\n186\tIncremental training (1≤m≤M-1)\n187\t{ μy  | y ∈L0 ∪ L1...∪ Lm-1 }\n188\ti\n189\ti\n190\ttr\n191\tStep1:\n192\ts\n193\tt\n194\tt\n195\tStep2:\n196\t \n197\tFigure 1: Framework of our method. In base training, we learn \n198\tdomain-invariant embeddings via adversarial contrastive training \n199\tusing a spectral disruptor. In incremental training, we freeze the \n200\tencoder and update the classifier with embeddings of new classes \n201\tsamples and mean vectors of old classes’ embeddings. 𝛼, 𝛽, 𝜆: three \n202\tadjustable coefficients; ℓ௖௘\n203\t௡௘௪: cross-entropy loss ℓ௖௘ on embeddings \n204\tof new classes; ℓୡୣ\n205\t୭௟ௗ: ℓ௖௘ on mean vectors of old classes’ embeddings; \n206\tMLP: multi-layer perceptron; 𝝁௬೔: mean vectors of embeddings for \n207\tclass 𝑦௜; Lm: label set in session m. \n208\tFigure 1 shows our method’s framework which includes base \n209\t(m=0) and incremental (1≤m≤(M-1)) training sessions. The \n210\tmodel consists of an encoder and a classifier. The log Mel- \n211\tspectrogram of audio samples are used as the input of the model. \n212\tTo increase the diversity of adversarial samples, we design a \n213\tspectral disruptor used in the adversarial contrastive training to \n214\tperturb the time-frequency elements of the log Mel- \n215\tspectrogram. The spectral disruptor includes two random \n216\tconvolutional layers with the same parameters [31], which is \n217\tinitialized with normal distribution and is frozen in the \n218\tgeneration of adversarial samples. The kernel size is selected \n219\trandomly from a candidate pool. The stride and padding are set \n220\tto preserve the shape of log Mel-spectrogram. In the base \n221\tsession, the model is trained by an adversarial contrastive \n222\ttraining strategy for extracting domain-invariant embeddings. \n223\tIn each incremental session, the encoder is frozen to preserve \n224\tthe knowledge of base classes, while the classifier is updated to \n225\tenable the model to recognize new classes. In inference, cosine \n226\tdistance between embeddings and classifier weights is used to \n227\tidentify each test sample.  \n228\tIn the base training session, each training episode includes \n229\ttwo steps, i.e., generating adversarial samples and training the \n230\tmodel. In the first step, the model is frozen and the adversarial \n231\tsamples are generated based on the single source domain \n232\tsamples by maximizing the loss ℓ௠௔௫ (defined by Eq. 7). In \n233\tthe second step, the model is trained by minimizing the loss \n234\tℓ௠௜௡ (defined by Eq. 8) using both the generated adversarial \n235\tsamples and source domain samples. To mitigate the model’s \n236\tforgetting of old classes, the mean vector of embeddings for \n237\tclass 𝑦௜ (𝑦௜∈𝑳଴∪⋯𝑳௠) is saved and computed by  \n238\t𝝁௬೔=\n239\tଵ\n240\t௄∑\n241\t𝑓ா(𝒙௞)\n242\t௄\n243\t௞ୀଵ\n244\t ,                   (1) \n245\twhere K denotes the number of support samples per class; \n246\t𝑓ா(𝒙௞) denotes the embedding of sample 𝒙௞.  \n247\tIn the mth (1≤m) incremental training session, the classifier \n248\tis updated using mean vectors of old classes’ embeddings and \n249\tthe embeddings extracted from the samples in 𝑫௠\n250\t௧௥ by \n251\tminimizing the incremental loss ℓ௜௡௖ which is defined by \n252\tℓ௜௡௖= ℓ௖௘\n253\t௡௘௪+ 𝜆ℓ௖௘\n254\t௢௟ௗ,            (2) \n255\twhere 𝜆, ℓ௖௘\n256\t௡௘௪ and ℓ௖௘\n257\t௢௟ௗ denote an adjustable coefficient, the \n258\tcross-entropy loss ℓ௖௘ on the training data of the mth session \n259\tand the ℓ௖௘ on the mean vectors of old classes’ embeddings, \n260\trespectively. ℓ௖௘ is defined by \n261\tℓ௖௘((𝒙௜, 𝑦௜);  𝜃) = −𝑙𝑜𝑔\n262\tୣ୶୮ (ఎ⋅cos(௙ಶ(𝒙೔), 𝒄೤೔))\n263\t∑\n264\tୣ୶୮ቀఎ⋅cos(௙ಶ(𝒙೔), 𝒄೤ೕ)ቁ\n265\tಿ\n266\t೤ೕసభ\n267\t， (3) \n268\twhere 𝜃= {𝐸, 𝐶}  represents the model, consisting of an \n269\tencoder E and a classifier C. 𝒄௬೔ is the weight vector \n270\tcorresponding to the j-th class. η, exp(‧) and cos(‧,‧) are a scale \n271\tfactor, exponential and cosine functions, respectively.  \n272\t2.3. Adversarial Contrastive Training \n273\tAn adversarial contrastive training strategy is proposed to make \n274\tthe learned embeddings domain-invariant, intra-class compact, \n275\tand inter-class separable. Building upon the framework of \n276\tadversarial training [19]-[22], the problem of single source-\n277\tdomain generalization can be formulated by \n278\tmin\n279\tఏsup\n280\t஽೟\n281\t{𝔼[ℓ(𝐷௦;  𝜃): 𝑑(𝐷௧, 𝐷௦) ≤𝜌]},      (4) \n282\twhere 𝐷௦ and 𝐷௧ are the distributions of source and target \n283\tdomains, respectively. 𝜌 is the maximum distance constraint \n284\tbetween 𝐷௦ and 𝐷௧. 𝑑(𝐷௧, 𝐷௦) denotes the distance between \n285\t𝐷௦ and 𝐷௧, and is defined by \n286\t  𝑑(𝐷௧, 𝐷௦) = ‖𝑓ா(𝒙௦) −𝑓ா(𝒙௧)‖ଶ\n287\tଶ+ ∞⋅1 {𝑦௧≠𝑦௦},  (5) \n288\twhere 𝒙௦ (or 𝒙௧) and 𝑦௦ (or 𝑦௧) are the samples and \n289\tcorresponding labels from source (or target) domains, \n290\trespectively. Eq. 5 defines the distance metric as Euclidean for \n291\tsamples with the same label and infinity for those with different \n292\tlabels. This ensures semantic consistency between source \n293\tdomain samples and the generated adversarial samples. The \n294\tsolution to Eq. 4 guarantees good performance of the model 𝜃 \n295\tfor all target distributions 𝐷௧ satisfying 𝑑(𝐷௧, 𝐷௦) ≤𝜌 [20]. \n296\tSpecifically, the sup{⋅} problem serves to identify the worst-\n297\tcase target distribution 𝐷௧ by maximizing the expectation of \n298\tloss ℓ, namely 𝔼[ℓ] . The min{⋅}  problem optimizes the \n299\t\n300\t\n301\t=== PAGE 3 ===\n302\tmodel’s parameters 𝜃 by minimizing 𝔼[ℓ]. After iterations of \n303\toptimization, the model learns embeddings that are robust to all \n304\tdistributions bounded by 𝜌. The Lagrangian relaxation derived \n305\tfrom Eq. 4 with a penalty 𝛾≥0 is used here, namely \n306\tmin\n307\tఏsup\n308\t஽೟\n309\t{𝔼[ℓ(𝐷௧;  𝜃)] −𝛾𝑑(𝐷௧, 𝐷௦)}.      (6) \n310\tFollowing [19], the problem in Eq. 6 can be solved through \n311\talternating maximizing and minimizing training steps. \n312\tIn the maximizing training step, the model is frozen and the \n313\tadversarial samples are generated by maximizing ℓ௠௔௫ \n314\tℓ௠௔௫= ℓ௖௘((𝒙௧, 𝑦௦);  𝜃) −𝛾𝑑൫(𝒙௧, 𝑦௦), (𝒙௦, 𝑦௦)൯. (7) \n315\tIn the minimizing training step, the adversarial samples \n316\tgenerated in the maximizing step and the source domain \n317\tsamples are used to train the model by minimizing loss ℓ௠௜௡. \n318\tTo mitigating few-shot overfitting, we integrate the supervised \n319\tcontrastive loss [18] into ℓ௠௜௡. This reinforces intra-class \n320\tcompactness and inter-class separability, pre-structuring a \n321\tdiscriminative \n322\tembedding \n323\tspace \n324\tthat \n325\tfacilitates \n326\tthe \n327\testablishment of robust decision boundaries for new classes \n328\twith a few samples. Accordingly, ℓ௠௜௡ is defined by \n329\tℓ௠௜௡= 𝛼ℓ௖௘+ 𝛽ℓ௦௖௟,            (8) \n330\twhere 𝛼 and 𝛽 are two adjustable coefficients; ℓ௦௖௟ is \n331\tdefined by \n332\tℓ௦௖௟= ∑\n333\tିଵ\n334\t|ூ(௕)|\n335\t௕ఢ஻\n336\t∑\n337\t𝑙𝑜𝑔\n338\t௘௫௣൫ఛ௙ಶ\n339\tᇲ(𝒙್)⋅௙ಶ\n340\tᇲ(𝒙೔)൯\n341\t∑\n342\t௘௫௣൫ఛ௙ಶ\n343\tᇲ(𝒙್)⋅௙ಶ\n344\tᇲ(𝒙ೕ)൯\n345\tೕసಲ(್)\n346\t௜ఢூ(௕)\n347\t , (9) \n348\twhere 𝐵, 𝜏, 𝒙௕, and 𝒙௜ denote the index set of samples in a \n349\ttraining episode, a scale factor, anchor sample, and positive \n350\tsample of the same class as 𝒙௕, respectively. 𝑓ா\n351\tᇱ(⋅) is the \n352\tembedding of 𝑓ா(⋅) output by the MLP. For  any  index 𝑏 , \n353\t𝐼(𝑏) = {𝑖𝜖𝐴(𝑏)|𝑦௜= 𝑦௕}  stands for the set of indices that \n354\tshare the same label as 𝒙௕. 𝐴(𝑏) = 𝐵\\{𝑏} denotes the index \n355\tset except b. The process of the adversarial contrastive training \n356\tstrategy is summarized as Algorithm 1, as shown in Table 1. \n357\tTable 1: Algorithm 1 Adversarial contrastive training. \n358\tInput: training dataset 𝑫଴\n359\t௧௥ from source domain; \n360\tRequire: learning rate ζ௠௔௫ and ζ௠௜௡; epoch number R  \n361\tOutput: the trained model 𝜃 in base session \n362\t1.While minimizing training do \n363\t2.  Select audio samples from 𝑫଴\n364\t௧௥and extract its log-Mel \n365\tspectrogram (𝑿௦, 𝒀௦)  \n366\t3.  While maximizing training do \n367\t4.    𝑿௧←Spectral disturbance on 𝑿௦  \n368\t5.    For R epochs do \n369\t6.     𝑿௧←𝑿௧+ ζ𝑚𝑎𝑥∇𝑿೟(ℓ௖௘((𝑿௧, 𝒀௦);  𝜃) −𝛾𝑑((𝑿௧, 𝒀௦), (𝑿௦, 𝒀௦)))\n370\t7.    End For \n371\t8.  End While \n372\t9.  𝑿= [𝑿௦, 𝑿௧], 𝒀= [𝒀௦, 𝒀௦] \n373\t10.  𝜃←𝜃−ζ௠௜௡∇ఏℓ௠௜௡(𝑿, 𝒀; 𝜃) \n374\t11. End While \n375\t3. Experiments \n376\t3.1. Experimental Datasets \n377\tTable 2: Detailed information of the LS-100/NSynth -100/FSC-89. \n378\tParam \n379\tD0 \n380\tDm (1 ≤ m ≤ (M-1))\n381\t𝑫଴\n382\t௧௥ \n383\t𝑫଴\n384\t௧௘ \n385\t𝑫௠\n386\t௧௥ \n387\t𝑫௠\n388\t௧௘\n389\t#C \n390\t60/55/59 \n391\t60/55/59 \n392\t40/45/30 \n393\t40/45/30\n394\tL(h) \n395\t16.66/12.23 \n396\t/13.11 \n397\t3.33/1.52 \n398\t/3.28 \n399\t11.11/5.00 \n400\t/4.17 \n401\t2.22/5.00 \n402\t/1.67\n403\t#S/C \n404\t500/200/800 \n405\t100/100/200\n406\t500/100/500 \n407\t100/100/200\n408\t#C: number of classes, L(h): Length(hours) #S/C: number of samples per class. \n409\tExperimental data are from three public datasets, including the \n410\tLS-100, NSynth-100 and FSC-89 [17]. They are widely used in \n411\tprior work, and released at the three websites1. Each dataset is \n412\tsplit into M parts, namely Dm (0 ≤ m ≤ (M-1)), without overlaps \n413\tof classes. Dm consists of training dataset 𝑫௠\n414\t௧௥ and testing \n415\tdataset 𝑫௠\n416\t௧௘. Table 2 lists the details of the three datasets, in \n417\twhich each digit X, Y and Z in the X/Y/Z represent the contents \n418\tfor the LS-100, NSynth-100 and FSC-89, respectively. For \n419\texample, 60/55/59 denotes that the number of classes for the \n420\tLS-100, NSynth-100 and FSC-89 is 60, 55 and 59, respectively.  \n421\tThese three datasets are adopted to construct six pairs of \n422\tcross-domain datasets, namely FS→NS, FS→LS, NS→FS, \n423\tNS→LS, LS→FS and LS→NS，where LS, NS and FS denote \n424\tLS_100, NS-100 and FSC_89, respectively. For example, in the \n425\tFS→NS, the item on the left side of the arrow (i.e., FS) denotes \n426\tthe source domain data (namely D0 of FSC-89), and the item on \n427\tthe right side of the arrow (i.e., NS) denotes the target domain \n428\tdata (namely Dm (1 ≤ m ≤ (M-1)) of NSynth-100). \n429\tThe usage of the above cross-domain datasets is based on two \n430\tconsiderations. First, we need to address the problems of both \n431\tdomain shift (cross-domain) and class increment (cross-class) \n432\tin this paper. The FSC-89, NSynth-100 and LS-100 have \n433\tdifferent audio classes and are recorded in different \n434\tenvironments using various recording devices. Hence, there are \n435\tboth domain shift and class increment between the above three \n436\tdatasets. Second, the construction of the above cross-domain \n437\tdatasets meets the requirements of practical applications. For \n438\texample, in smart home application scenarios, the humanoid \n439\trobots deployed with audio classification models are required \n440\tto incrementally recognize voice commands (speech dataset), \n441\tenvironmental sound (sound-event dataset), and musical \n442\tsounds (musical-instrument dataset) from different domains. \n443\t3.2. Experimental Setup \n444\tAverage Accuracy (AA) is adopted to measure the overall \n445\tperformance of various methods in all sessions and defined by \n446\t𝐴𝐴=\n447\tଵ\n448\tெ∑\n449\t𝐴௠\n450\tெିଵ\n451\t௠ୀ଴\n452\t ,            (10) \n453\twhere 𝐴௠ denotes the accuracy in session m. \n454\tFollowing the practice of [10]-[15], we use ResNet-18 [30] \n455\tas the encoder. In the base session, the model is trained for 200 \n456\tepochs. Each epoch has 50 episodic training steps. In each \n457\tepisodic training step, NK support samples and NQ query \n458\tsamples are randomly chosen from 𝑫௠\n459\t௧௥. In each incremental \n460\tsession, the model is trained for 100 epochs. All testing datasets \n461\tof seen classes are used to evaluate the model. Dimensions of \n462\tlog Mel- spectrogram and embeddings are set to 128 and 512, \n463\trespectively. Coefficients 𝛼, 𝛽, 𝛾, λ, and learning rate are set \n464\tto 1, 0.2, 1, 0.6, and 0.1, respectively. \n465\t3.3. Ablation Experiments \n466\tTable 3: Results obtained by different methods on NS→LS. \n467\tCa-\n468\tse  SC AT\n469\tAccuracy scores in various sessions (%) \n470\tAA \n471\t(%)\n472\t0\n473\t1 \n474\t2 \n475\t3 \n476\t4 \n477\t5 \n478\t6 \n479\t7 \n480\t8 \n481\t①×\n482\t× 99.96 88.97 83.45 78.21 73.27 68.99 65.43 62.01 58.84 75.46\n483\t②√\n484\t×\n485\t100.00 91.75 85.15 79.28 74.32 69.97 66.10 62.58 59.36 76.50\n486\t③×\n487\t√99.94 92.40 86.73 80.98 75.74 71.28 67.99 64.39 61.13 77.84\n488\t④√\n489\t√99.93 94.13 88.38 82.52 77.15 72.85 69.17 65.43 62.22 79.09\n490\tSC: Supervised Contrastive loss; AT: Adversarial Training. \n491\tThis section discusses the contributions of Supervised \n492\tContrastive loss (SC) and Adversarial Training (AT) to the \n493\tperformance of our method. Without the loss of generality, the \n494\tNS→LS is used in ablation and extended experiments. Table 3 \n495\tlists the results of our method with various combinations of SC \n496\tand AT on the NS→LS. In case ①, the model is trained by \n497\t\n498\t\n499\t=== PAGE 4 ===\n500\tminimizing ℓ௖௘ without SC and AT in the base session. In \n501\tcases ② and ③, the model is trained by minimizing ℓ௖௘ \n502\tusing SC and AT only, respectively. Based on the results in all \n503\tfour cases, it can be obtained that the SC and AT contribute to \n504\tthe performance gain. When both of them are used (case ④), \n505\tour method obtains the highest AA scores of 79.09%. \n506\t3.4. Comparison of Different Methods  \n507\tOur method is compared to nine baseline methods, including \n508\tthe DFSL [10], CEC [27], PAN [11], AMFO [15], AMFO+TSA, \n509\tAMFO+LDP, AMFO+AFA, AMFO+AMTF and PCR [28]. \n510\tAmong them, the DFSL, CEC, PAN and AMFO are the FCAC \n511\tmethods without considering cross domain. The AMFO+TSA, \n512\tAMFO+LDP, AMFO+AFA and AMFO+AMTF are the \n513\tcombination of both few-shot cross-domain methods (namely \n514\tTSA [25], LDP [26], AFA [21] and AMTF [22]) and the FCAC \n515\tmethod (namely AMFO). PCR is a method of cross-domain \n516\tfew-shot class-incremental point cloud recognition, where the \n517\tproblem setting is the same to ours.  \n518\tThe DFSL method designs an attentive weight generator for \n519\tproducing classifier weight vectors to adapt to new classes. The \n520\tCEC method designs a graph model to propagate contextual \n521\tinformation between classifiers. The PAN method designs self-\n522\tattention modified prototypes to expand classifier. The AMFO \n523\tmethod adopts discriminative and generalizable classifier and \n524\tembeddings. The TSA method uses lightweight parametric \n525\tadapters, allowing task-specific adaptation. The LDP method \n526\tuses local and global distillation prototype network to improve \n527\tthe generalizability of embeddings. The AFA method adopts \n528\tthe adversarial feature augmentation to bridge the domain gap \n529\tin few-shot learning. The AMTF method adopts a meta-training \n530\tstrategy to improve the generalization ability of existing \n531\tmethods in few-shot learning. The PCR method distinguishes \n532\tbetween base classes and new classes from an out-of-\n533\tdistribution detection perspective.  \n534\tFollowing the practice of [10]-[16], the value of (N, K) is \n535\ttypically set to (5, 5). The AA scores of both source and target \n536\tdomain classes obtained by different methods on the six pairs \n537\tof cross-domain datasets are listed in Table 4. Our method \n538\tachieves AA scores of 46.89%, 41.67% 85.17%, 79.09%, 80.05% \n539\tand 79.78% on the FS→NS, FS→LS, NS→FS, NS→LS, LS→\n540\tFS and LS→NS, respectively. The above AA scores are higher \n541\tthan the counterparts obtained by other methods. The advantage \n542\tof our method in AA is mainly attributed to the adversarial \n543\tcontrastive training strategy. The strategy enables the model to \n544\textract \n545\tdomain-invariant \n546\tembeddings \n547\twith \n548\tintra-class \n549\tcompactness and inter-class separability. Thus, our model has \n550\tstrong generalization ability for unseen domains and classes. \n551\tTable 4: Average accuracy obtained by various methods (in %). \n552\tMethods \n553\tFS→NS FS→LS NS→FS NS→LS LS→FS LS→NS\n554\tDFSL \n555\t37.21 \n556\t37.54 \n557\t82.58 \n558\t76.62 \n559\t77.83\n560\t75.30\n561\tCEC \n562\t40.75 \n563\t39.29 \n564\t83.75 \n565\t77.31 \n566\t78.57\n567\t76.86\n568\tPAN \n569\t40.88 \n570\t39.35 \n571\t83.83 \n572\t77.50 \n573\t78.71\n574\t77.34\n575\tAMFO \n576\t45.31 \n577\t37.05 \n578\t83.86 \n579\t76.93 \n580\t78.10\n581\t71.92\n582\tAMFO+TSA \n583\t44.13 \n584\t36.24 \n585\t84.19 \n586\t77.24 \n587\t78.21\n588\t78.20\n589\tAMFO+LDP \n590\t43.30 \n591\t33.61 \n592\t84.70 \n593\t77.40 \n594\t76.35\n595\t72.60\n596\tAMFO+AFA \n597\t44.75 \n598\t41.52 \n599\t84.46 \n600\t78.50 \n601\t79.47\n602\t78.68\n603\tAMFO+AMTF 44.29 \n604\t40.76 \n605\t83.93 \n606\t77.95 \n607\t79.11\n608\t78.21\n609\tPCR \n610\t38.70 \n611\t36.98 \n612\t75.61 \n613\t78.22 \n614\t78.79\n615\t78.80\n616\tOurs \n617\t46.89 \n618\t41.67 \n619\t85.17 \n620\t79.09 \n621\t80.05\n622\t79.78\n623\tIn addition, we perform two extended experiments. In the \n624\tfirst extended experiment, we discuss the impacts of N and K \n625\tvalues on the AA scores obtained by our method. Figure 2 \n626\tdepicts the results obtained by our method on the NS→LS when \n627\tN-way K-shot is set to different values. When N is fixed, the \n628\tAA score steadily increases as K grows. The reason for the \n629\tabove result is that the larger the K value, the more training \n630\tsamples for each class, and the better the model performance. \n631\tWhen K is fixed, the AA scores reach the maximum when N \n632\tequals 5. If N decreases below 5, the number of sessions \n633\tincreases and then the model easily forgets old classes. \n634\tTherefore, the AA scores will decrease. If N increases over 5, \n635\tthe number of classes per session increases. Hence, heavier \n636\tconfusions of different classes will occur in each session and \n637\tthus the AA scores will decline accordingly. \n638\t \n639\tFigure 2: AA scores (in %) obtained by our method on the NS→LS using \n640\tvarious values of N-way K-shot.  \n641\tIn the second extended experiment, we use t-SNE [29] to \n642\tshow the effectiveness of the adversarial contrastive training \n643\tstrategy. Figure 3 visualizes the testing embeddings without \n644\tusing or using the proposed strategy on the NS→LS, where five \n645\tsource and target classes are randomly selected from the \n646\tNSynth-100 and LS-100, respectively. As shown in Fig. 3 (a), \n647\twithout using the adversarial contrastive training strategy, the \n648\tembeddings of most target domain classes overlap each other, \n649\tand they also overlap with the embeddings of source-domain \n650\tclasses. The reason is that the encoder trained solely on source \n651\tdomain data fails to extract discriminative embeddings for the \n652\ttarget domain. Fig. 3 (b) shows that our method using the \n653\tproposed strategy makes the testing embeddings of various \n654\tclasses distribute in different places with almost no overlap.  \n655\t \n656\t \n657\t(a)                           (b) \n658\tFigure 3: Distributions of testing embeddings of five source and target \n659\tclasses on the NS→LS (a) without using and (b) using the proposed \n660\tadversarial contrastive training strategy.  \n661\t4. Conclusions \n662\tWe solved the CD-FCAC problem via the adversarial training \n663\tand supervised contrastive loss. Based on the description of our \n664\tmethod and results, we can draw two conclusions. First, our \n665\tmethod exceeds state-of-the-art methods in average accuracy. \n666\tSecond, the proposed adversarial contrastive training strategy \n667\tbenefits to improve the model’s performance. In next work, we \n668\twill enhance the accuracy by designing more effective encoder \n669\tand classifier. \n670\t1 https://www.modelscope.cn/datasets/pp199124903/LS-100/summary  \n671\thttps://www.modelscope.cn/datasets/pp199124903/FSC-89/summary  \n672\thttps://www.modelscope.cn/datasets/pp199124903/NSynth-100/summary\n673\t\n674\t\n675\t=== PAGE 5 ===\n676\t5. Acknowledgements \n677\tThis work was supported by the national natural science \n678\tfoundation of China (62371195, 62111530145, 61771200), the \n679\texchange project of the 10th Meeting of the China-Croatia \n680\tScience and Technology Cooperation Committee (No. 10-34).  \n681\t6. Generative AI Use Disclosure \n682\tNo generative AI tools (e.g., LLM/ChatGPT) were used to \n683\tproduce any part of this work, except that a limited amount of \n684\tgrammar/spelling checking may have been performed on the \n685\tfinal text using standard tools. The authors take full \n686\tresponsibility for the content. \n687\t7. References \n688\t[1] A. Terni, N. Ortolani, I. Nolasco, E. Bonitos, and S. Cecchi, \n689\t“Comparison of feature extraction methods for sound-based \n690\tclassification of honey bee activity,” IEEE/ACM TASLP, vol. 30, \n691\tpp. 112-122, 2022. \n692\t[2] Y. Li, X. Li, Y. Zhang, M. Liu, and W. Wang, “Anomalous sound \n693\tdetection using deep audio representation and a BLSTM network \n694\tfor audio surveillance of roads,” IEEE Access, vol. 6, pp. 58043-\n695\t58055, 2018. \n696\t[3] Y. Li, J. Tan, G. Chen, J. Li, Y. Si, and Q. He, “Low-complexity \n697\tacoustic scene classification using parallel attention-convolution \n698\tnetwork,” in Proc. of Interspeech, 2024, pp. 1-5.  \n699\t[4] W. Pang, et al., “Detecting video anomalies by jointly utilizing \n700\tappearance and skeleton information,” Expert Syst. Appl., vol. 246, \n701\tpp. 1-12, 2024. \n702\t[5] Y. Li, W. Wang, M. Liu, Z. Jiang, and Q. He, “Speaker clustering \n703\tby co-optimizing deep representation learning and cluster \n704\testimation,” IEEE TMM, vol. 23, pp. 3377-3387, 2021. \n705\t[6] Y.-X. Lin, J.-C. Lin, W.-L. Wei and J.-C. Wang, “Learnable \n706\tcounterfactual attention for music classification,” IEEE TASLP, vol. \n707\t33, pp. 570-585, 2025. \n708\t[7] M. Agarwal, K. S. Gill, S. Chattopadhyay and M. Singh, \n709\t“Classification of urban sound using sequential convolutional \n710\tneural network model and its visualisation,” in Proc. of ICITEICSI, \n711\t2024, pp. 1-5.  \n712\t[8] K. M. Lim, C. P. Lee, Z. Y. Lee, J. Y. Lim and J. N. Mogan, \n713\t“Acoustic event classification with enhanced efficientNet,” in Proc. \n714\tof ICSPC, 2024, pp. 13-17. \n715\t[9] S. Barahona, D. de Benito-Gorrón, D. T. Toledano and D. Ramos, \n716\t“Enhancing conformer-based sound event detection using \n717\tfrequency dynamic convolutions and beats audio embeddings,” \n718\tIEEE/ACM TASLP, vol. 32, pp. 3896-3907, 2024. \n719\t[10] Y. Wang, N. J. Bryan, M. Cartwright, J. P. Bello, and J. Salomon, \n720\t“Few shot continual learning for audio classification,” in Proc. of \n721\tIEEE ICASSP, 2021, pp. 321-325. \n722\t[11] Y. Li, W. Cao, W. Xian, J. Li, and E. Benito’s, “Few-shot class-\n723\tincremental audio classification using dynamically expanded \n724\tclassifier with self-attention modified prototypes,” IEEE TMM, \n725\tvol.26, pp.1346-1360, 2024. \n726\t[12] W. Xie, et al., “Few-shot class-incremental audio classification via \n727\tdiscriminative prototype learning,” Expert Syst. Appl., vol. 225, \n728\t2023, Art. no. 120044. \n729\t[13] W. Xie, et al., “Few-shot class-incremental audio classification \n730\tusing adaptively-refined prototypes,” in Proc. of Interspeech, 2023, \n731\tpp. 301-305. \n732\t[14] Y. Li, W. Cao, J. Li, W. Xie, and Q. He, “Few-shot class-\n733\tincremental audio classification using stochastic classifier,” in Proc. \n734\tof Interspeech, 2023, pp. 4174-4178. \n735\t[15] Y. Li, J. Li, Y. Si, J. Tan, and Q. He, “Few-shot class-incremental \n736\taudio classification with adaptive mitigation of forgetting and \n737\toverfitting,” IEEE/ACM TASLP, vol. 32, pp. 2297-2311, 2024. \n738\t[16] Y. Si, Y. Li, J. Tan, G. Chen, Q. Li, and M. Russo, “Fully few-shot \n739\tclass-incremental audio classification with adaptive improvement \n740\tof stability and plasticity,” IEEE TASLP, vol. 33, pp. 418-433, 2025.  \n741\t[17] Y. Si, Y. Li, J. Tan, Q. He, and I. Kwak, “Fully few-shot class-\n742\tincremental audio classification using multi-level embedding \n743\textractor and ridge regression classifier,” in Proc. of Interspeech, \n744\t2025, pp. 1318-1322. \n745\t[18] P. Khosla, P. Teterwak, C. Wang, A. Sarna, Y. Tian, P. Isola, A. \n746\tMaschinot, C. Liu, and D. Krishnan, “Supervised contrastive \n747\tlearning,” in Proc. of NIPS, 2020. pp. 18661-18673. \n748\t[19] A. Sinha, H. Namkoong, and J. Duchi, “Certifying some \n749\tdistributional robustness with principled adversarial training,” in \n750\tProc. of International Conference on Learning Representations, \n751\t2018, pp. 1-34. \n752\t[20] R. Volpi, H. Namkoong, O. Sener, and J.C. Duchi, V. Murino, and \n753\tS. Savarese, “Generalizing to unseen domains via adversarial data \n754\taugmentation,” in Proc. of Advances in Neural Information \n755\tProcessing Systems, 2018, pp. 1-11. \n756\t[21] Y. Hu, A.J. Ma, “Adversarial feature augmentation for cross-\n757\tdomain few-shot classification,” in Proc. of ECCV, 2022, pp. 20-37. \n758\t[22] P. Tian, and S. Xie, “An adversarial meta-training framework for \n759\tcross-domain \n760\tfew-shot \n761\tlearning,\" \n762\tIEEE \n763\tTransactions \n764\ton \n765\tMultimedia, vol. 25, pp. 6881-6891, 2023. \n766\t[23] K. Lee, K. Lee, J. Shin, and H. Lee, “Network randomization: A \n767\tsimple technique for generalization in deep reinforcement learning,” \n768\tin Proc. of ICLR, 2020, pp. 1-22. \n769\t[24] X. Glorot, and Y. Bengio, “Understanding the difficulty of training \n770\tdeep feedforward neural networks,” in Proc. of the thirteenth \n771\tinternational conference on artificial intelligence and statistics, \n772\t2010, pp. 249-256. \n773\t[25] W. Li, X. Liu and H. Bilen, \"Cross-domain Few-shot Learning \n774\twith Task-specific Adapters,\" in Proc. of CVPR, 2022, pp. 7151-\n775\t7160, \n776\t[26] F. Zhou, P. Wang, L. Zhang, W. Wei and Y. Zhang, \"Revisiting \n777\tPrototypical Network for Cross Domain Few-Shot Learning,\" in \n778\tProc. Of CVPR, 2023, pp. 20061-20070. \n779\t[27] C. Zhang, N. Song, G. Lin, Y. Zheng, P. Pan, and Y. Xu, “Few-\n780\tshot incremental learning with continually evolved classifiers,” in \n781\tProc. of CVPR, 2021, pp. 12450 -1245. \n782\t[28] Y. Tan, and X. Xiang, “Cross-domain few-shot incremental \n783\tlearning for point-cloud recognition,” in Proc. of IEEE/CVF Winter \n784\tConference on Applications of Computer Vision, 2024, pp. 2296-\n785\t2305. \n786\t[29] L. V. D. Maaten, and G. Hinton, “Visualizing data using T-SNE,” \n787\tJ. Mach. Learn. Res., vol. 9, no. 96, pp. 2579-2605, 2008. \n788\t[30] K. He, X. Zhang, S. Ren and J. Sun, \"Deep Residual Learning for \n789\tImage Recognition,\" in Proc. of IEEE CVPR, 2016, 1022 pp. 770-\n790\t778. \n791\t[31] Kimin Lee, Kibok Lee, Jinwoo Shin, and Honglak Lee. Network \n792\trandomization: A simple technique for generalization in deep \n793\treinforcement learning. in Proc. of IEEE ICLR, 2020. \n794\t\n795\t\n796\t\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]}, "parent_tool_use_id": null, "session_id": "7ec66818-554e-4d8f-82de-03e202721698", "uuid": "653c4578-f972-4381-8abc-15dffc086151", "timestamp": "2026-07-12T09:57:11.435Z", "tool_use_result": {"type": "text", "file": {"filePath": "/inspire/qb-ilm/project/video-generation/chenxie-25019/hyr/iHateTheWorld555.github.io/.claude-review/projects/-inspire-qb-ilm-project-video-generation-chenxie-25019-hyr-iHateTheWorld555-github-io/7ec66818-554e-4d8f-82de-03e202721698/tool-results/bqpm8hgiv.txt", "content": "=== PAGE 1 ===\n Cross Domain Few-Shot Class-Incremental Audio Classification Via \nAdversarial Contrastive Learning  \nYongjie Si, Yanxiong Li*, Sen Huang, Beibei Liu  \nSchool of Electronic and Information Engineering, South China University of Technology, Guangzhou, China  \neeyongjiesi@mail.scut.edu.cn, eeyxli@scut.edu.cn, huangsen@scut.edu.cn, eebbliu@scut.edu.cn \n \nAbstract \nCurrent Few-shot Class-incremental Audio Classification \n(FCAC) methods assume that samples of base and incremental \nclasses are in the same domain (following the same distribution). \nHowever, there is generally a domain shift between the above \ntwo types of samples. In this paper, we explore the problem of \nCross Domain FCAC where samples of base and incremental \nclasses have domain shift. We propose a strategy of adversarial \ncontrastive training which enables the model to effectively \nclassify samples of different classes from unseen domains. The \nmodel consists of an encoder and a classifier. The encoder is \ntrained in base session but frozen in incremental sessions, \nwhereas the classifier is trained in all sessions. Experiments are \ndone on six pairs of cross-domain datasets. Results show that \nour method exceeds state-of-the-art methods in average \naccuracy. The code is at https://github.com/YongjieSi/ACL. \nIndex Terms: Few-shot class-incremental learning, audio \nclassification, cross domain, adversarial contrastive learning \n1. Introduction \nAudio classification (AC) is a task to identify different audio \nclasses. It has widespread applications, such as wildlife \nprotection [1], road surveillance [2], classification of acoustic \nscene [3], video analysis [4] and speaker analysis [5]. Many AC \nmethods [6]-[9] require abundant samples of predefined classes \nfor model training. The trained model generally lacks the ability \nto recognize new classes. In real applications, the number of \nclasses is not fixed but dynamically changes and the number of \ntraining samples per class is generally limited. To address \nchallenges such as the variable number of classes and scarcity \nof training samples per class, Few-shot Class-incremental \nAudio Classification (FCAC) methods are proposed [10]-[16]. \nThey can continually identify new classes using a few training \nsamples per class and meanwhile memorize old ones. A \ncommon practice in the FCAC methods is to decompose the \nmodel into an encoder and a classifier. Existing FCAC methods \nhave different technical characteristics, such as Dynamic Few-\nShot Learning (DFSL) [10], prototype-based classifier [11]-\n[13], stochastic classifier [14], linear classifier [15], [16], and \nridge regression classifier [17].  \nThe above efforts have contributed to the development of \nAC, but they still leave something to be improved. For example, \nthese methods assume that the samples of different classes in \nboth base and incremental sessions are from the same domain. \nHowever, there is a domain shift between the samples from base \nand incremental sessions in many applications. In this paper, we \ntackle a new and practical problem in which domain shift and \nclass increment coexist in different session. This problem is \ncalled Cross Domain FCAC (CD-FCAC). It is an extension of \nthe FCAC problem which does not consider the domain shift of \nsamples from different sessions. To our best knowledge, the \nwork in this paper is the first effort to solve the CD-FCAC \nproblem. The motivation for doing this work is due to the \nexistence of CD-FCAC problems in many practical applications. \nFor example, in smart home scenarios, the intelligent agents \nneed to incrementally recognize different audio classes (such as \nvoice commands, environmental sounds, and musical sounds) \nfrom different domains (e.g., different datasets). \nIn addition to the catastrophic forgetting of old classes in \nincremental learning, there are two key challenges in the CD-\nFCAC. First, there is domain shift between samples of both \nbase and incremental classes. Second, there is label difference \nbetween base and incremental classes. To obtain high accuracy, \nthe model needs to have strong ability to overcome the impacts \nof class increment and domain shift. To address the above two \nchallenges, we propose a strategy of adversarial contrastive \ntraining which adopts both adversarial training and contrastive \nloss. To alleviate domain shift, diverse adversarial samples are \ngenerated to simulate pseudo-target domains. They and the \nsource-domain samples are used together to train the model for \nextracting domain-invariant embeddings. To enable the model \nto generalize well to unseen classes, we use the loss of \nsupervised contrastive learning for training the model in the \nbase session. This loss aims to aggregate the embeddings of \nsamples of the same class while keeping the embeddings of \nsamples of different classes away from each other. Hence, the \nembeddings are expected to be intra-class compact and inter-\nclass separable, which allows the classifier to establish robust \ndecision boundaries based on a few samples of new classes. To \nprevent the model from forgetting the knowledge of old classes, \nthe encoder is frozen and mean vectors of old classes’ \nembeddings are saved in each incremental session, while the \nclassifier is updated for learning new classes in each session. \nExperiments are done on six pairs of cross-domain datasets \nfrom three public datasets of the LS-100, NSynth-100, and \nFSC-89 [17]. Results show that our method exceeds previous \nmethods in average accuracy. The contributions of the work are \nsummarized as follows. \n1) We explore a new problem of CD-FCAC where the \ndomain shift and class increment coexist.  \n2) We propose an adversarial contrastive training strategy \nwhich is a fusion of adversarial training and contrastive learning.  \n3) We propose a CD-FCAC method which exceeds state-\nof-the-art methods in average accuracy.  \n2. Method \n2.1. Problem Definition \nThe CD-FCAC consists of M sessions, including one base \nsession (session 0) and (M-1) incremental sessions (sessions 1 \nto (M-1)). we consider a user-friendly setting where the samples \n \n* Corresponding author: Yanxiong Li (eeyxli@scut.edu.cn).\n\n\n=== PAGE 2 ===\nin base session are from a single source domain, while the \nsamples in incremental sessions are from another domain. The \nbase classes (in the base session) and incremental classes (in the \nincremental sessions) are called source-domain classes and \ntarget-domain classes, respectively. In addition, audio classes \nin the prior and current sessions are called old and new classes, \nrespectively. The training and testing datasets of different \nsessions are {𝑫଴\n௧௥, 𝑫ଵ\n௧௥, ..., 𝑫௠\n௧௥, ..., 𝑫ெିଵ\n௧௥\n} and {𝑫଴\n௧௘, 𝑫ଵ\n௧௘, ..., \n𝑫௠\n௧௘, ..., 𝑫ெିଵ\n௧௘\n}, respectively. 𝑫௠\n௧௥ and 𝑫௠\n௧௘ have the same \nlabel set Lm. The datasets in various sessions don’t have the \nsame classes, namely ∀m, h and m ≠ h, Lm ∩ Lh = ϕ. In the mth \nsession, only 𝑫௠\n௧௥ can be used to train the model, and the \ntrained model is tested on the testing datasets of current and all \nprevious sessions, namely 𝑫଴\n௧௘∪𝑫ଵ\n௧௘...∪𝑫௠\n௧௘. The dataset 𝑫଴\n௧௥ \nhas many classes and each class has sufficient training samples, \nwhile the dataset 𝑫௠\n௧௥ (1≤m≤(M-1)) only has N classes and \neach class only has K training samples.  \n2.2. Method Framework \nEncoder\nSource domain audio \nsamples   from  D0\nLog Mel-spectra X \nClassifier\nSpectral disruptor\nℓmax\n: Frozen\n: Active\nMLP\ntr\nℓce\nℓscl\n: Forward\nGenerating adversarial samples\n(Maximizing training step)\nℓmin\nEncoder\nAdversarial samples  X \nClassifier\nC\nα\nβ\n Training the model\n(Minimizing training step)\n: Backward\nBase training（m=0）\nLog Mel-\nspectra X \nAudio \nsamples Dm\nClassifier\nEncoder\n λ\nℓinc\nℓce\nℓce\nnew\nold\nIncremental training (1≤m≤M-1)\n{ μy  | y ∈L0 ∪ L1...∪ Lm-1 }\ni\ni\ntr\nStep1:\ns\nt\nt\nStep2:\n \nFigure 1: Framework of our method. In base training, we learn \ndomain-invariant embeddings via adversarial contrastive training \nusing a spectral disruptor. In incremental training, we freeze the \nencoder and update the classifier with embeddings of new classes \nsamples and mean vectors of old classes’ embeddings. 𝛼, 𝛽, 𝜆: three \nadjustable coefficients; ℓ௖௘\n௡௘௪: cross-entropy loss ℓ௖௘ on embeddings \nof new classes; ℓୡୣ\n୭௟ௗ: ℓ௖௘ on mean vectors of old classes’ embeddings; \nMLP: multi-layer perceptron; 𝝁௬೔: mean vectors of embeddings for \nclass 𝑦௜; Lm: label set in session m. \nFigure 1 shows our method’s framework which includes base \n(m=0) and incremental (1≤m≤(M-1)) training sessions. The \nmodel consists of an encoder and a classifier. The log Mel- \nspectrogram of audio samples are used as the input of the model. \nTo increase the diversity of adversarial samples, we design a \nspectral disruptor used in the adversarial contrastive training to \nperturb the time-frequency elements of the log Mel- \nspectrogram. The spectral disruptor includes two random \nconvolutional layers with the same parameters [31], which is \ninitialized with normal distribution and is frozen in the \ngeneration of adversarial samples. The kernel size is selected \nrandomly from a candidate pool. The stride and padding are set \nto preserve the shape of log Mel-spectrogram. In the base \nsession, the model is trained by an adversarial contrastive \ntraining strategy for extracting domain-invariant embeddings. \nIn each incremental session, the encoder is frozen to preserve \nthe knowledge of base classes, while the classifier is updated to \nenable the model to recognize new classes. In inference, cosine \ndistance between embeddings and classifier weights is used to \nidentify each test sample.  \nIn the base training session, each training episode includes \ntwo steps, i.e., generating adversarial samples and training the \nmodel. In the first step, the model is frozen and the adversarial \nsamples are generated based on the single source domain \nsamples by maximizing the loss ℓ௠௔௫ (defined by Eq. 7). In \nthe second step, the model is trained by minimizing the loss \nℓ௠௜௡ (defined by Eq. 8) using both the generated adversarial \nsamples and source domain samples. To mitigate the model’s \nforgetting of old classes, the mean vector of embeddings for \nclass 𝑦௜ (𝑦௜∈𝑳଴∪⋯𝑳௠) is saved and computed by  \n𝝁௬೔=\nଵ\n௄∑\n𝑓ா(𝒙௞)\n௄\n௞ୀଵ\n ,                   (1) \nwhere K denotes the number of support samples per class; \n𝑓ா(𝒙௞) denotes the embedding of sample 𝒙௞.  \nIn the mth (1≤m) incremental training session, the classifier \nis updated using mean vectors of old classes’ embeddings and \nthe embeddings extracted from the samples in 𝑫௠\n௧௥ by \nminimizing the incremental loss ℓ௜௡௖ which is defined by \nℓ௜௡௖= ℓ௖௘\n௡௘௪+ 𝜆ℓ௖௘\n௢௟ௗ,            (2) \nwhere 𝜆, ℓ௖௘\n௡௘௪ and ℓ௖௘\n௢௟ௗ denote an adjustable coefficient, the \ncross-entropy loss ℓ௖௘ on the training data of the mth session \nand the ℓ௖௘ on the mean vectors of old classes’ embeddings, \nrespectively. ℓ௖௘ is defined by \nℓ௖௘((𝒙௜, 𝑦௜);  𝜃) = −𝑙𝑜𝑔\nୣ୶୮ (ఎ⋅cos(௙ಶ(𝒙೔), 𝒄೤೔))\n∑\nୣ୶୮ቀఎ⋅cos(௙ಶ(𝒙೔), 𝒄೤ೕ)ቁ\nಿ\n೤ೕసభ\n， (3) \nwhere 𝜃= {𝐸, 𝐶}  represents the model, consisting of an \nencoder E and a classifier C. 𝒄௬೔ is the weight vector \ncorresponding to the j-th class. η, exp(‧) and cos(‧,‧) are a scale \nfactor, exponential and cosine functions, respectively.  \n2.3. Adversarial Contrastive Training \nAn adversarial contrastive training strategy is proposed to make \nthe learned embeddings domain-invariant, intra-class compact, \nand inter-class separable. Building upon the framework of \nadversarial training [19]-[22], the problem of single source-\ndomain generalization can be formulated by \nmin\nఏsup\n஽೟\n{𝔼[ℓ(𝐷௦;  𝜃): 𝑑(𝐷௧, 𝐷௦) ≤𝜌]},      (4) \nwhere 𝐷௦ and 𝐷௧ are the distributions of source and target \ndomains, respectively. 𝜌 is the maximum distance constraint \nbetween 𝐷௦ and 𝐷௧. 𝑑(𝐷௧, 𝐷௦) denotes the distance between \n𝐷௦ and 𝐷௧, and is defined by \n  𝑑(𝐷௧, 𝐷௦) = ‖𝑓ா(𝒙௦) −𝑓ா(𝒙௧)‖ଶ\nଶ+ ∞⋅1 {𝑦௧≠𝑦௦},  (5) \nwhere 𝒙௦ (or 𝒙௧) and 𝑦௦ (or 𝑦௧) are the samples and \ncorresponding labels from source (or target) domains, \nrespectively. Eq. 5 defines the distance metric as Euclidean for \nsamples with the same label and infinity for those with different \nlabels. This ensures semantic consistency between source \ndomain samples and the generated adversarial samples. The \nsolution to Eq. 4 guarantees good performance of the model 𝜃 \nfor all target distributions 𝐷௧ satisfying 𝑑(𝐷௧, 𝐷௦) ≤𝜌 [20]. \nSpecifically, the sup{⋅} problem serves to identify the worst-\ncase target distribution 𝐷௧ by maximizing the expectation of \nloss ℓ, namely 𝔼[ℓ] . The min{⋅}  problem optimizes the \n\n\n=== PAGE 3 ===\nmodel’s parameters 𝜃 by minimizing 𝔼[ℓ]. After iterations of \noptimization, the model learns embeddings that are robust to all \ndistributions bounded by 𝜌. The Lagrangian relaxation derived \nfrom Eq. 4 with a penalty 𝛾≥0 is used here, namely \nmin\nఏsup\n஽೟\n{𝔼[ℓ(𝐷௧;  𝜃)] −𝛾𝑑(𝐷௧, 𝐷௦)}.      (6) \nFollowing [19], the problem in Eq. 6 can be solved through \nalternating maximizing and minimizing training steps. \nIn the maximizing training step, the model is frozen and the \nadversarial samples are generated by maximizing ℓ௠௔௫ \nℓ௠௔௫= ℓ௖௘((𝒙௧, 𝑦௦);  𝜃) −𝛾𝑑൫(𝒙௧, 𝑦௦), (𝒙௦, 𝑦௦)൯. (7) \nIn the minimizing training step, the adversarial samples \ngenerated in the maximizing step and the source domain \nsamples are used to train the model by minimizing loss ℓ௠௜௡. \nTo mitigating few-shot overfitting, we integrate the supervised \ncontrastive loss [18] into ℓ௠௜௡. This reinforces intra-class \ncompactness and inter-class separability, pre-structuring a \ndiscriminative \nembedding \nspace \nthat \nfacilitates \nthe \nestablishment of robust decision boundaries for new classes \nwith a few samples. Accordingly, ℓ௠௜௡ is defined by \nℓ௠௜௡= 𝛼ℓ௖௘+ 𝛽ℓ௦௖௟,            (8) \nwhere 𝛼 and 𝛽 are two adjustable coefficients; ℓ௦௖௟ is \ndefined by \nℓ௦௖௟= ∑\nିଵ\n|ூ(௕)|\n௕ఢ஻\n∑\n𝑙𝑜𝑔\n௘௫௣൫ఛ௙ಶ\nᇲ(𝒙್)⋅௙ಶ\nᇲ(𝒙೔)൯\n∑\n௘௫௣൫ఛ௙ಶ\nᇲ(𝒙್)⋅௙ಶ\nᇲ(𝒙ೕ)൯\nೕసಲ(್)\n௜ఢூ(௕)\n , (9) \nwhere 𝐵, 𝜏, 𝒙௕, and 𝒙௜ denote the index set of samples in a \ntraining episode, a scale factor, anchor sample, and positive \nsample of the same class as 𝒙௕, respectively. 𝑓ா\nᇱ(⋅) is the \nembedding of 𝑓ா(⋅) output by the MLP. For  any  index 𝑏 , \n𝐼(𝑏) = {𝑖𝜖𝐴(𝑏)|𝑦௜= 𝑦௕}  stands for the set of indices that \nshare the same label as 𝒙௕. 𝐴(𝑏) = 𝐵\\{𝑏} denotes the index \nset except b. The process of the adversarial contrastive training \nstrategy is summarized as Algorithm 1, as shown in Table 1. \nTable 1: Algorithm 1 Adversarial contrastive training. \nInput: training dataset 𝑫଴\n௧௥ from source domain; \nRequire: learning rate ζ௠௔௫ and ζ௠௜௡; epoch number R  \nOutput: the trained model 𝜃 in base session \n1.While minimizing training do \n2.  Select audio samples from 𝑫଴\n௧௥and extract its log-Mel \nspectrogram (𝑿௦, 𝒀௦)  \n3.  While maximizing training do \n4.    𝑿௧←Spectral disturbance on 𝑿௦  \n5.    For R epochs do \n6.     𝑿௧←𝑿௧+ ζ𝑚𝑎𝑥∇𝑿೟(ℓ௖௘((𝑿௧, 𝒀௦);  𝜃) −𝛾𝑑((𝑿௧, 𝒀௦), (𝑿௦, 𝒀௦)))\n7.    End For \n8.  End While \n9.  𝑿= [𝑿௦, 𝑿௧], 𝒀= [𝒀௦, 𝒀௦] \n10.  𝜃←𝜃−ζ௠௜௡∇ఏℓ௠௜௡(𝑿, 𝒀; 𝜃) \n11. End While \n3. Experiments \n3.1. Experimental Datasets \nTable 2: Detailed information of the LS-100/NSynth -100/FSC-89. \nParam \nD0 \nDm (1 ≤ m ≤ (M-1))\n𝑫଴\n௧௥ \n𝑫଴\n௧௘ \n𝑫௠\n௧௥ \n𝑫௠\n௧௘\n#C \n60/55/59 \n60/55/59 \n40/45/30 \n40/45/30\nL(h) \n16.66/12.23 \n/13.11 \n3.33/1.52 \n/3.28 \n11.11/5.00 \n/4.17 \n2.22/5.00 \n/1.67\n#S/C \n500/200/800 \n100/100/200\n500/100/500 \n100/100/200\n#C: number of classes, L(h): Length(hours) #S/C: number of samples per class. \nExperimental data are from three public datasets, including the \nLS-100, NSynth-100 and FSC-89 [17]. They are widely used in \nprior work, and released at the three websites1. Each dataset is \nsplit into M parts, namely Dm (0 ≤ m ≤ (M-1)), without overlaps \nof classes. Dm consists of training dataset 𝑫௠\n௧௥ and testing \ndataset 𝑫௠\n௧௘. Table 2 lists the details of the three datasets, in \nwhich each digit X, Y and Z in the X/Y/Z represent the contents \nfor the LS-100, NSynth-100 and FSC-89, respectively. For \nexample, 60/55/59 denotes that the number of classes for the \nLS-100, NSynth-100 and FSC-89 is 60, 55 and 59, respectively.  \nThese three datasets are adopted to construct six pairs of \ncross-domain datasets, namely FS→NS, FS→LS, NS→FS, \nNS→LS, LS→FS and LS→NS，where LS, NS and FS denote \nLS_100, NS-100 and FSC_89, respectively. For example, in the \nFS→NS, the item on the left side of the arrow (i.e., FS) denotes \nthe source domain data (namely D0 of FSC-89), and the item on \nthe right side of the arrow (i.e., NS) denotes the target domain \ndata (namely Dm (1 ≤ m ≤ (M-1)) of NSynth-100). \nThe usage of the above cross-domain datasets is based on two \nconsiderations. First, we need to address the problems of both \ndomain shift (cross-domain) and class increment (cross-class) \nin this paper. The FSC-89, NSynth-100 and LS-100 have \ndifferent audio classes and are recorded in different \nenvironments using various recording devices. Hence, there are \nboth domain shift and class increment between the above three \ndatasets. Second, the construction of the above cross-domain \ndatasets meets the requirements of practical applications. For \nexample, in smart home application scenarios, the humanoid \nrobots deployed with audio classification models are required \nto incrementally recognize voice commands (speech dataset), \nenvironmental sound (sound-event dataset), and musical \nsounds (musical-instrument dataset) from different domains. \n3.2. Experimental Setup \nAverage Accuracy (AA) is adopted to measure the overall \nperformance of various methods in all sessions and defined by \n𝐴𝐴=\nଵ\nெ∑\n𝐴௠\nெିଵ\n௠ୀ଴\n ,            (10) \nwhere 𝐴௠ denotes the accuracy in session m. \nFollowing the practice of [10]-[15], we use ResNet-18 [30] \nas the encoder. In the base session, the model is trained for 200 \nepochs. Each epoch has 50 episodic training steps. In each \nepisodic training step, NK support samples and NQ query \nsamples are randomly chosen from 𝑫௠\n௧௥. In each incremental \nsession, the model is trained for 100 epochs. All testing datasets \nof seen classes are used to evaluate the model. Dimensions of \nlog Mel- spectrogram and embeddings are set to 128 and 512, \nrespectively. Coefficients 𝛼, 𝛽, 𝛾, λ, and learning rate are set \nto 1, 0.2, 1, 0.6, and 0.1, respectively. \n3.3. Ablation Experiments \nTable 3: Results obtained by different methods on NS→LS. \nCa-\nse  SC AT\nAccuracy scores in various sessions (%) \nAA \n(%)\n0\n1 \n2 \n3 \n4 \n5 \n6 \n7 \n8 \n①×\n× 99.96 88.97 83.45 78.21 73.27 68.99 65.43 62.01 58.84 75.46\n②√\n×\n100.00 91.75 85.15 79.28 74.32 69.97 66.10 62.58 59.36 76.50\n③×\n√99.94 92.40 86.73 80.98 75.74 71.28 67.99 64.39 61.13 77.84\n④√\n√99.93 94.13 88.38 82.52 77.15 72.85 69.17 65.43 62.22 79.09\nSC: Supervised Contrastive loss; AT: Adversarial Training. \nThis section discusses the contributions of Supervised \nContrastive loss (SC) and Adversarial Training (AT) to the \nperformance of our method. Without the loss of generality, the \nNS→LS is used in ablation and extended experiments. Table 3 \nlists the results of our method with various combinations of SC \nand AT on the NS→LS. In case ①, the model is trained by \n\n\n=== PAGE 4 ===\nminimizing ℓ௖௘ without SC and AT in the base session. In \ncases ② and ③, the model is trained by minimizing ℓ௖௘ \nusing SC and AT only, respectively. Based on the results in all \nfour cases, it can be obtained that the SC and AT contribute to \nthe performance gain. When both of them are used (case ④), \nour method obtains the highest AA scores of 79.09%. \n3.4. Comparison of Different Methods  \nOur method is compared to nine baseline methods, including \nthe DFSL [10], CEC [27], PAN [11], AMFO [15], AMFO+TSA, \nAMFO+LDP, AMFO+AFA, AMFO+AMTF and PCR [28]. \nAmong them, the DFSL, CEC, PAN and AMFO are the FCAC \nmethods without considering cross domain. The AMFO+TSA, \nAMFO+LDP, AMFO+AFA and AMFO+AMTF are the \ncombination of both few-shot cross-domain methods (namely \nTSA [25], LDP [26], AFA [21] and AMTF [22]) and the FCAC \nmethod (namely AMFO). PCR is a method of cross-domain \nfew-shot class-incremental point cloud recognition, where the \nproblem setting is the same to ours.  \nThe DFSL method designs an attentive weight generator for \nproducing classifier weight vectors to adapt to new classes. The \nCEC method designs a graph model to propagate contextual \ninformation between classifiers. The PAN method designs self-\nattention modified prototypes to expand classifier. The AMFO \nmethod adopts discriminative and generalizable classifier and \nembeddings. The TSA method uses lightweight parametric \nadapters, allowing task-specific adaptation. The LDP method \nuses local and global distillation prototype network to improve \nthe generalizability of embeddings. The AFA method adopts \nthe adversarial feature augmentation to bridge the domain gap \nin few-shot learning. The AMTF method adopts a meta-training \nstrategy to improve the generalization ability of existing \nmethods in few-shot learning. The PCR method distinguishes \nbetween base classes and new classes from an out-of-\ndistribution detection perspective.  \nFollowing the practice of [10]-[16], the value of (N, K) is \ntypically set to (5, 5). The AA scores of both source and target \ndomain classes obtained by different methods on the six pairs \nof cross-domain datasets are listed in Table 4. Our method \nachieves AA scores of 46.89%, 41.67% 85.17%, 79.09%, 80.05% \nand 79.78% on the FS→NS, FS→LS, NS→FS, NS→LS, LS→\nFS and LS→NS, respectively. The above AA scores are higher \nthan the counterparts obtained by other methods. The advantage \nof our method in AA is mainly attributed to the adversarial \ncontrastive training strategy. The strategy enables the model to \nextract \ndomain-invariant \nembeddings \nwith \nintra-class \ncompactness and inter-class separability. Thus, our model has \nstrong generalization ability for unseen domains and classes. \nTable 4: Average accuracy obtained by various methods (in %). \nMethods \nFS→NS FS→LS NS→FS NS→LS LS→FS LS→NS\nDFSL \n37.21 \n37.54 \n82.58 \n76.62 \n77.83\n75.30\nCEC \n40.75 \n39.29 \n83.75 \n77.31 \n78.57\n76.86\nPAN \n40.88 \n39.35 \n83.83 \n77.50 \n78.71\n77.34\nAMFO \n45.31 \n37.05 \n83.86 \n76.93 \n78.10\n71.92\nAMFO+TSA \n44.13 \n36.24 \n84.19 \n77.24 \n78.21\n78.20\nAMFO+LDP \n43.30 \n33.61 \n84.70 \n77.40 \n76.35\n72.60\nAMFO+AFA \n44.75 \n41.52 \n84.46 \n78.50 \n79.47\n78.68\nAMFO+AMTF 44.29 \n40.76 \n83.93 \n77.95 \n79.11\n78.21\nPCR \n38.70 \n36.98 \n75.61 \n78.22 \n78.79\n78.80\nOurs \n46.89 \n41.67 \n85.17 \n79.09 \n80.05\n79.78\nIn addition, we perform two extended experiments. In the \nfirst extended experiment, we discuss the impacts of N and K \nvalues on the AA scores obtained by our method. Figure 2 \ndepicts the results obtained by our method on the NS→LS when \nN-way K-shot is set to different values. When N is fixed, the \nAA score steadily increases as K grows. The reason for the \nabove result is that the larger the K value, the more training \nsamples for each class, and the better the model performance. \nWhen K is fixed, the AA scores reach the maximum when N \nequals 5. If N decreases below 5, the number of sessions \nincreases and then the model easily forgets old classes. \nTherefore, the AA scores will decrease. If N increases over 5, \nthe number of classes per session increases. Hence, heavier \nconfusions of different classes will occur in each session and \nthus the AA scores will decline accordingly. \n \nFigure 2: AA scores (in %) obtained by our method on the NS→LS using \nvarious values of N-way K-shot.  \nIn the second extended experiment, we use t-SNE [29] to \nshow the effectiveness of the adversarial contrastive training \nstrategy. Figure 3 visualizes the testing embeddings without \nusing or using the proposed strategy on the NS→LS, where five \nsource and target classes are randomly selected from the \nNSynth-100 and LS-100, respectively. As shown in Fig. 3 (a), \nwithout using the adversarial contrastive training strategy, the \nembeddings of most target domain classes overlap each other, \nand they also overlap with the embeddings of source-domain \nclasses. The reason is that the encoder trained solely on source \ndomain data fails to extract discriminative embeddings for the \ntarget domain. Fig. 3 (b) shows that our method using the \nproposed strategy makes the testing embeddings of various \nclasses distribute in different places with almost no overlap.  \n \n \n(a)                           (b) \nFigure 3: Distributions of testing embeddings of five source and target \nclasses on the NS→LS (a) without using and (b) using the proposed \nadversarial contrastive training strategy.  \n4. Conclusions \nWe solved the CD-FCAC problem via the adversarial training \nand supervised contrastive loss. Based on the description of our \nmethod and results, we can draw two conclusions. First, our \nmethod exceeds state-of-the-art methods in average accuracy. \nSecond, the proposed adversarial contrastive training strategy \nbenefits to improve the model’s performance. In next work, we \nwill enhance the accuracy by designing more effective encoder \nand classifier. \n1 https://www.modelscope.cn/datasets/pp199124903/LS-100/summary  \nhttps://www.modelscope.cn/datasets/pp199124903/FSC-89/summary  \nhttps://www.modelscope.cn/datasets/pp199124903/NSynth-100/summary\n\n\n=== PAGE 5 ===\n5. Acknowledgements \nThis work was supported by the national natural science \nfoundation of China (62371195, 62111530145, 61771200), the \nexchange project of the 10th Meeting of the China-Croatia \nScience and Technology Cooperation Committee (No. 10-34).  \n6. Generative AI Use Disclosure \nNo generative AI tools (e.g., LLM/ChatGPT) were used to \nproduce any part of this work, except that a limited amount of \ngrammar/spelling checking may have been performed on the \nfinal text using standard tools. The authors take full \nresponsibility for the content. \n7. References \n[1] A. Terni, N. Ortolani, I. Nolasco, E. Bonitos, and S. Cecchi, \n“Comparison of feature extraction methods for sound-based \nclassification of honey bee activity,” IEEE/ACM TASLP, vol. 30, \npp. 112-122, 2022. \n[2] Y. Li, X. Li, Y. Zhang, M. Liu, and W. Wang, “Anomalous sound \ndetection using deep audio representation and a BLSTM network \nfor audio surveillance of roads,” IEEE Access, vol. 6, pp. 58043-\n58055, 2018. \n[3] Y. Li, J. Tan, G. Chen, J. Li, Y. Si, and Q. He, “Low-complexity \nacoustic scene classification using paralle